definition.value: A  3-nitrotyrosine comprising L-tyrosine having a nitro group at the 3-position on the phenyl ring.
An N-acylamino acid consisting of 6-aminohexanoic acid bearing an N-(4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
A uridine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-O-methyl derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.
A 2-amino-2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose with an alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
A hydroxypolyether aldehyde comprising hexaethylene glycol having one of the terminal hydroxy groups substituted by formylmethoxy.
A tetrahydroxytetrahydrofuran in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 2, 3, 4, and 4 and which is substituted by a methyl group at position 2 (the 2R,4S diastereoisomer).

A 2-acetyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine betaine which has hexadecyl as the alkyl group. PAF is a potent phospholipid activator and mediator of many leukocyte functions, including platelet aggregation, inflammation, and anaphylaxis.
A hydroxypolyether that is the monomethyl ether derivative of diethylene glycol.
An alkyl alcohol that is pentane in which a hydrogen of one of the methyl groups is substituted by a hydroxy group. It has been isolated from Melicope ptelefolia.
A poly(ethylene glycol) that is octane-1,8-diol in which the carbon atoms at positions 3 and 6 have been replaced by oxygen atoms.
A C-nitro compound that is the N-(p-nitrophenylphosphobutyryl) derivative of glycine; a cognate transition state analogue of the esterase-like catalytic antibody D2.3.
A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 6.8 at 20 degreeC.
A monovalent inorganic anion obtained by deprotonation of hydroxyphosphanone.
An N-[4-(4-nitrophenylphospho)butanoyl]alanine that has R at the chiral carbon.
A trivalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of all three protons from phosphorous acid.
The potassium salt of diclofenac.
A penicillin that is 6-aminopenicillanic acid in which one of the amino hydrogens is replaced by a 3-(2,6-dichlorophenyl)-5-methyl-1,2-oxazol-4-yl]formyl group.

An organofluorine compound that is 4-benzoylpyrazole in which the phenyl is substituted at position 3 by a (2,3-dihydroxypropyl)oxy group and in which the pyrazole moiety is substituted at positions 1 and 5 by a 4-fluorophenyl group and an amino group, respectively.
A branched, short-chain fatty acid composed of propanoic acid having two methyl substituents at the 2-position.
An optically active version of thioproline having L-configuration.
A 1-acyl-2-dodecanoyl-sn-glycerol-3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl group is also dodecanoyl (lauroyl).
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from diphosphoric acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine where the two phosphatidyl acyl groups are specified as tetradecanoyl (myristoyl).

An amino cyclitol glycoside that is 4,6-diaminocyclohexane-1,2,3-triol having a 2,6-diamino-2,6-dideoxy-alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 1 and a beta-D-ribosyl residue attached at position 2. It is an antibiotic produced by Streptomyces ribosidificus (formerly S. thermoflavus).

A monocarboxylic acid amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of pyrazinoic acid (pyrazine-2-carboxylic acid) with ammonia. A prodrug for pyrazinoic acid, pyrazinecarboxamide is used as part of multidrug regimens for the treatment of tuberculosis.
A straight-chain alkane with 16 carbon atoms. It is a component of essential oil isolated from long pepper.

A quinolone that is pefloxacin in which the ethyl group at position 1 of the quinolone has been replaced by a p-fluorophenyl group. A broad-spectrum antibiotic effective against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, it is used (usually as the monohydrochloride salt) for the treatment of bacterial infections in dogs.
A sulfonamide in which the sulfamoyl functional group is attached to aniline at the 4-position.
An optically active tetramine epitope consisting of three separate amino substituents attached to a central carbon.
A benzoic acid derivative carrying 3-, 4- and 5-methoxy substituents.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2-methylbutanoic acid.
A hexitol that is 1-deoxy derivative of L-mannitol.
